The Version Control & Automation Layer (The Trigger)Source of Truth: All infrastructure configurations are stored in a Git repository (like GitHub or GitLab).  CI/CD Pipeline: Instead of applying code locally, pipelines automatically run terraform plan on every pull request, and terraform apply on merge. This enforces peer review and eliminates manual provisioning steps.  

The Modular Core (The Building Blocks)To achieve that 25% improvement in environment consistency, the architecture relies on standardized templates rather than hard-coded scripts.  Network Module: A reusable VPC configuration that guarantees every environment has the exact same subnet, NAT gateway, and route table structure.  Compute Module: Standardized EKS cluster setups, enforcing the same logging and node group defaults across the board.  Security Module: Reusable IAM roles and policies to ensure least privilege access without having to rewrite JSON policies every time.  

State & Drift Management Layer (The Anchor)This is the specific mechanism that solves the "configuration drift" problem you highlighted.  Remote State Backend (AWS S3 / Azure Blob): Stores the terraform.tfstate file centrally so the entire team works from the exact same mapping of reality.State Locking (DynamoDB): Prevents two engineers (or pipelines) from running deployments at the same time, avoiding state corruption.Drift Detection: Scheduled CI/CD runs check the remote state against the actual live cloud environment to catch unauthorized manual changes instantly.

Multi-Cloud Targets (The Destinations)The modular engine is designed to seamlessly target both AWS and Azure environments based on provider blocks, allowing for flexible cloud application development and deployment. 

